 housing that is connected both to the city and the landscape. This new fabric is made out of 100 residential towers, each with a footprint of 9m x 14m and a height of 100 meters. To provide the gradual interior articulation compatible with the ambiguities and nuances of contemporary life, the apartments are organized in levels and articulated by large cylindrical columns that, playing the role of inhabitable structure, provide protection against earthquakes and efficiently manage the flows of air, water, power and people up and down the building.","post_title":"<p>Ascoli Nuovissimo, Ascoli Pisceno, IT 2013-2014<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"ascoli-nuovissimo","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-05-09 22:48:19","post_modified_gmt":"2017-05-09 22:48:19","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=76","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw"},{"ID":1184,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2017-04-06 15:20:09","post_date_gmt":"2017-04-06 15:20:09","post_content":"At the corner of the City Park of Dessau, the building for the <em>Bauhaus Museum<\/em> literally binds together its collection, the temporary exhibits and the city itself. Aspiring to resist the rigor mortis that descends upon things canonized into museums all over the world, the building is organized as a continuous loop feeding off future temporary exhibitions and the city itself to inject continued relevance and vitality into the enduring legacy of the Bauhaus. Back at the Temporary Exhibit Gallery overlooking the Foyer below, visitors can either descend to the entry level or recommence the exhibition cycle again for a closer look at items that might have captured their interest. Made flexible by shortcut connections that allow the visitors to design their own trajectories, this exhibition loop provides conceptual clarity to the structure of the galleries and invites the possibility of repetition, potentially encouraging a more profound knowledge of The Bauhaus Collection. It is said that the future changes the past: the strong continuity between Temporary Exhibits and Permanent Collection generated by the closed loop trajectory encourages, with each new temporary exhibit, the potential of generating fresh views on the history of the Bauhaus, contributing to the vitality of its cultural legacy.","post_title":"<p>Bauhaus Museum Dessau, DE 2015<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"bauhaus-museum-dessau-de-2015","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-05-10 16:40:41","post_modified_gmt":"2017-05-10 16:40:41","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=1184","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw"},{"ID":1146,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2017-04-05 23:41:39","post_date_gmt":"2017-04-05 23:41:39","post_content":"The <em>Beijing Line Tower<\/em> is made of a beam of light, round stainless steel mirrors and a wood frame. The tower measures approximately 10 meters high and 6 meters in diameter. By night, a line of light bounces between stainless steel mirrors tracing against the dark sky a 3-dimensional drawing of green fluorescent glow. This drawing can be changed and perfected by climbing on the stairs and adjusting the mirrors. Its form, defined by the straightness of the green laser light beam and the angle it forms at each mirror, can be contained but not fully controlled. The tower is an attempt to free drawing, free it from paper, canvas, and the interior of rooms, to take drawing outside and use it to bamboozle the eye with apparent complexity, then propel it up to the sky to a faint demise of atmospheric dissolution. The Beijing Line Tower's ancestry\u2014the photographs of shadows by Alexander Rodchenko, the luminous theatrical costumes of Oskar Schlemmer, Sol Le Witt's wall drawings, Fred Sandback's string drawings, Lebbeus Woods' installations\u2014can be traced down the annals of a fascination for freedom, freedom of the line from its paper support that is. During the day, the mirrors shine in the sunlight occasionally projecting a glimpse of the passing star moving in the sky.","post_title":"<p>Beijing Line Tower, Siracusa, IT 2014<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"beijing-line-tower-siracusa-it-2014","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-05-15 16:13:02","post_modified_gmt":"2017-05-15 16:13:02","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=1146","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw"},{"ID":384,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2017-03-28 03:49:00","post_date_gmt":"2017-03-28 03:49:00","post_content":"Tripods face each other across the floor suggesting an invisible geometry of space. They split the room into behind-between-beyond (or before-during-after). Seen metaphorically, they can be the scale models for a city of the future, a city of towers five hundred meters tall, one half of the space given to urban parks, a human density twice that of Hong Kong with the air full of blue triangular light. Seen objectively, they are six-meter-tall, one-and-a-half-millimeter-thick, steel lattice tripods, their surface formed by strips of three centimeters placed every twelve centimeters. The tripods have a footprint of thirty-four centimeters by \u202fthirty-four centimeters, two arms or legs rising at thirty degrees from the vertical, one to four meters seventy centimeters and the other to three meters twenty centimeters.","post_title":"<p>Beijing Tripod, Beijing, CN 2008<\/p>","post