"Set on a 5-acre property overlooking an agricultural reserve, the <em>Centrifugal Villa<\/em>\u00a0includes a pool house with a separate guesthouse and garage structure. Designed as wood post-and-beam structure, the exterior cladding is detailed with vertical board and batten seams to give continuity to the building exterior and encourage a uninterrupted rhythmic flow around the elevations. With its narrow section and large dormer windows, the enjoyment and use of the house during the day requires no artificial lighting, and natural cross-ventilation is easily felt throughout the house. The <em>Centrifugal Villa<\/em> is arranged around a hollow center, as if the heart of the house had somehow fallen outside its body (which is not to suggest it is a house without a heart, only that it is not self-centered). The string of subsequent rooms in its interior keeps the whole together by sacrificing their individual geometric coherence to the fractured configuration of the entire composition.","post_title":"<p>Centrifugal Villa, Southampton, US 2005<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"cetrifugal-villa-southampton-us-2005","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-06-07 20:10:22","post_modified_gmt":"2017-06-07 20:10:22","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=590","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw"},{"ID":1160,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2017-04-06 14:43:48","post_date_gmt":"2017-04-06 14:43:48","post_content":"This public space is conjured out of the alliance of humans and nature, using the dense low bush of birch trees already there on the site to mold a series of perfectly geometric void \u201curban\u201d spaces in which the new and old buildings of the church will be contained. These are then connected through thresholds in the forest and programmed flexibly with space for various possible communal activities such as festivals, assemblies, outdoor services, etc. The church building is a sequence of spaces containing each other and leading people from the socially shared to the intimately personal. Geometry and light also follow this trajectory, suggesting a sequence from real to ideal: nature -&gt; polyhedron -&gt; sphere and exterior light + interior light -&gt; sacred penumbra. The oculus, the only source of light in the sanctuary, is located at the equinox azimuth of 20 degrees to capture the most amount of light throughout the year.","post_title":"<p>Church in the Arctic, Tana Bru,&nbsp;NO 2014<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"church-in-the-arctic-tana-bru-no-2014","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-05-15 18:59:40","post_modified_gmt":"2017-05-15 18:59:40","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=1160","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw"},{"ID":2167,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2018-01-09 18:43:45","post_date_gmt":"2018-01-09 18:43:45","post_content":"As a modest analogy of urban space, the design of this ephemeral structure aspires to a normative repetitiveness that risks certain dissolution of form and a numbing of the senses of the perception of spatial sequences. The project will define a certain rhythm of experience related to the time needed to negotiate arrays of overlapping trajectories which will be made subliminally legible through an insistence on certain thresholds sequences, some axial and some diagonal. The depth of the resulting layered space is sometimes revealed in the enfilades of doors that cut deep into the structure here and there as a perspectival projection of potential trajectories open to the visitors. Relying on the utmost geometric simplicity and the architectural resources that, as described above, can be easily missed or dismissed, the architectural design will recede perceptually to give primacy of place to the exhibited content, while at the same time trying to sustain it with a measure of discrete order. The structure, conceived as a repetitive grouping of small galleries, mostly 3 meters wide by 6 meters long, aims to create the atmosphere of repetitive neutrality necessary to contain all the unpredictable collision of richness the curatorial project proposes. The result is an undifferentiated labyrinth, one in which no proposed sequence of experience is particularly privileged and in which each visitor can trace his or her own personal trajectory. The only exceptions, three larger spaces for public assembly, are created not by adding anything to the project but by negatively subtracting walls and creating larger gaps.","post_title":"<p>Cities Exhibition, Imminent Commons, Seoul Biennale, KR 2017<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"cities-exhibition-imminent-commons-seoul-biennale-kr-2017","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2018-01-09 18:45:09","post_modified_gmt":"2018-01-09 18:45:09","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=2167","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw"},{"ID":1237,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2017-04-07 17:45:46","post_date_gmt":"2017-04-07 17:45:46","post_content":"In these times of severe environmental crisis, a <em>City of Science<\/em> is suggestive of something in-between having a perspective of renewed idealism and a resignation to conform to pure market strategies. In view of this epochal urgency, the project proposes to adopt healthier models of life in the interests of safeguarding the planet. Our proposal imagines the largest public park, the largest t