 exciting expansion plans. This sense of domesticity has a presence at the site that can be almost palpably felt when being there and must definitively be taken into account when proposing a project that would do justice to the institution\u2019s cultural importance and potential. Closely following the topography of the site, the upper part of the building is continuously suspended over the ground, containing in its interior three column-free galleries in a continuous spatial sequence connected through ramps and defined in simple clean planes bathed in flexibly controlled zenithal light.","post_title":"<p>Serlachius Museum Expansion,&nbsp;M&auml;ntt&auml;-Vilppula, FI 2011<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"serlachius-museum-mntt-fi-2011","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-06-05 15:44:14","post_modified_gmt":"2017-06-05 15:44:14","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=1131","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw"},{"ID":1189,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2017-04-06 16:03:12","post_date_gmt":"2017-04-06 16:03:12","post_content":"The <em>Seunsangga Citywalk<\/em> is here conceived as a spine of infrastructural potential\u00a0that maximizes and encourages variety and intensity in the use of public space. Going beyond circulation and commerce as the main uses of public space, it aspires to recast it as the locus of the unfolding of life\u2019s events for both citizens and visitors. The project is to embrace the essential paradox at the heart of urbanism: knowing next to nothing about the future, we still plan for it.\u00a0What will hold the project together is not spectacular and expensive form with which we would likely be tired of the day after tomorrow. Instead, the project will be realized with the maximum possible freedom of use of spaces 